User management with user-add, user-mod, and user-del.

These three commands all need sudo, and they are the low-level tools for managing accounts. The first, user-add, creates a new user. The single most important flag is dash m, which creates the home directory; forget it and you get a broken account with nowhere to live. Beyond that you will commonly set the login shell with dash s, the full name with dash c, and any supplementary groups with dash capital-g. Straight after creating an account it has no password and is locked, so you set one with the passwd command. There is also a friendlier, interactive front-end called add-user on the debian family that prompts you through everything; for scripts, stick with user-add.

The second command, user-mod, modifies an existing user, and it shares the same flags plus a few of its own: renaming, locking and unlocking, and changing the shell. Here lies the single most important gotcha in this whole notebook. When adding someone to a new group, you must write dash a dash capital-g together. The dash a means append. Without it, dash capital-g replaces all of the user's supplementary groups with just the one you named, silently removing them from everything else. So always append.

The third command, user-del, removes a user. On its own it deletes the account but leaves the home directory behind. With dash r it also removes the home directory and mail spool. Be careful with dash r, since it deletes the user's files, and before deleting anyone make sure no processes are still running under their name, which you can check with p-grep dash u.
